text: Should You Invest in the SPDR S&P Software & Services ETF (XSW)? Zacks Equity Research Tue, Jan 28, 2025, 2:20 PM 3 min read The SPDR S&P Software & Services ETF (XSW) was launched on 09/28/2011, and is a passively managed exchange traded fund designed to offer broad exposure to the Technology - Software segment of the equity market. An increasingly popular option among retail and institutional investors, passively managed ETFs offer low costs, transparency, flexibility, and tax efficiency; they are also excellent vehicles for long term investors. Additionally, sector ETFs offer convenient ways to gain low risk and diversified exposure to a broad group of companies in particular sectors. Technology - Software is one of the 16 broad Zacks sectors within the Zacks Industry classification. It is currently ranked 4, placing it in top 25%. Index Details The fund is sponsored by State Street Global Advisors. It has amassed assets over $525.26 million, making it one of the average sized ETFs attempting to match the performance of the Technology - Software segment of the equity market. XSW seeks to match the performance of the S&P Software & Services Select Industry Index before fees and expenses. The S&P Software & Services Select Industry Index represents the software sub-industry portion of the S&P Total Stock Market Index. The S&P TMI tracks all the U.S. common stocks listed on the NYSE, AMEX, NASDAQ National Market and NASDAQ Global Select Market. The Software Index is a modified equal weight index. Costs Investors should also pay attention to an ETF's expense ratio. Lower cost products will produce better results than those with a higher cost, assuming all other metrics remain the same. Annual operating expenses for this ETF are 0.35%, making it one of the least expensive products in the space. It has a 12-month trailing dividend yield of 0.07%. Sector Exposure and Top Holdings While ETFs offer diversified exposure, which minimizes single stock risk, a deep look into a fund's holdings is a valuable exercise. And, most ETFs are very transparent products that disclose their holdings on a daily basis. This ETF has heaviest allocation in the Information Technology sector--about 96.70% of the portfolio. Looking at individual holdings, D Wave Quantum Inc (QBTS) accounts for about 1.68% of total assets, followed by Soundhound Ai Inc A (SOUN) and Grid Dynamics Holdings Inc (GDYN). The top 10 holdings account for about 9.21% of total assets under management. Performance and Risk Year-to-date, the SPDR S&P Software & Services ETF has added roughly 1.02% so far, and is up about 27.60% over the last 12 months (as of 01/28/2025). XSW has traded between $141.27 and $204.72 in this past 52-week period. Story Continues The ETF has a beta of 1.16 and standard deviation of 28.79% for the trailing three-year period, making it a high risk choice in the space. With about 148 holdings, it effectively diversifies company-specific risk. Alternatives SPDR S&P Software & Services ETF holds a Zacks ETF Rank of 2 (Buy), which is based on expected asset class return, expense ratio, and momentum, among other factors. Because of this, XSW is an outstanding option for investors seeking exposure to the Technology ETFs segment of the market. There are other additional ETFs in the space that investors could consider as well. Invesco AI and Next Gen Software ETF (IGPT) tracks STOXX WORLD AC NEXGEN SOFTWARE DEV ID and the iShares Expanded Tech-Software Sector ETF (IGV) tracks S&P North American Technology-Software Index. Invesco AI and Next Gen Software ETF has $416.76 million in assets, iShares Expanded Tech-Software Sector ETF has $9.78 billion. IGPT has an expense ratio of 0.58% and IGV charges 0.41%. Grid Dynamics to Announce Fourth Quarter and Full Year 2024 Financial Results on February 20th Business Wire Wed, Jan 22, 2025, 12:05 AM 1 min read In This Article: GDYN +0.75% SAN RAMON, Calif., January 21, 2025 --( BUSINESS WIRE )-- Grid Dynamics Holdings, Inc. (Nasdaq: GDYN) ("Grid Dynamics"), a leader in enterprise-level digital transformation services and solutions, today announced that it will host a video conference call at 4:30 p.m. ET on Thursday, February 20, 2025 to discuss its fourth quarter and full year 2024 financial results. A press release containing these results will be available on our website prior to the call. A webcast of the video conference call, as well as a replay available after the event, can be accessed on the Investor Relations section of the company's website at https://www.griddynamics.com/investors . About Grid Dynamics Grid Dynamics (Nasdaq: GDYN) is a leading provider of technology consulting, platform and product engineering, AI, and digital engagement services. Fusing technical vision with business acumen, we solve the most pressing technical challenges and enable positive business outcomes for enterprise companies undergoing business transformation. A key differentiator for Grid Dynamics is our 8 years of experience and leadership in enterprise AI , supported by profound expertise and ongoing investment in data , analytics , application modernization , cloud platform and product engineering , and digital engagement services . Founded in 2006, Grid Dynamics is headquartered in Silicon Valley with offices across the Americas, Europe, and India. To learn more about Grid Dynamics, please visit http://www.griddynamics.com . Here's Why Grid Dynamics (GDYN) is a Great Momentum Stock to Buy Zacks Equity Research Fri, Dec 27, 2024, 8:00 PM 4 min read In This Article: GDYN +0.75% Momentum investing revolves around the idea of following a stock's recent trend in either direction. In the 'long' context, investors will be essentially be "buying high, but hoping to sell even higher." With this methodology, taking advantage of trends in a stock's price is key; once a stock establishes a course, it is more than likely to continue moving that way. The goal is that once a stock heads down a fixed path, it will lead to timely and profitable trades. While many investors like to look for momentum in stocks, this can be very tough to define. There is a lot of debate surrounding which metrics are the best to focus on and which are poor quality indicators of future performance. The Zacks Momentum Style Score, part of the Zacks Style Scores, helps address this issue for us. Below, we take a look at Grid Dynamics (GDYN) , a company that currently holds a Momentum Style Score of A. We also talk about price change and earnings estimate revisions, two of the main aspects of the Momentum Style Score. It's also important to note that Style Scores work as a complement to the Zacks Rank, our stock rating system that has an impressive track record of outperformance. Grid Dynamics currently has a Zacks Rank of #1 (Strong Buy). Our research shows that stocks rated Zacks Rank #1 (Strong Buy) and #2 (Buy) and Style Scores of A or B outperform the market over the following one-month period. You can see the current list of Zacks #1 Rank Stocks here >>> Set to Beat the Market? Let's discuss some of the components of the Momentum Style Score for GDYN that show why this company shows promise as a solid momentum pick. A good momentum benchmark for a stock is to look at its short-term price activity, as this can reflect both current interest and if buyers or sellers currently have the upper hand. It is also useful to compare a security to its industry, as this can help investors pinpoint the top companies in a particular area. For GDYN, shares are up 7.22% over the past week while the Zacks Computers - IT Services industry is down 1.34% over the same time period. Shares are looking quite well from a longer time frame too, as the monthly price change of 10.84% compares favorably with the industry's 0.21% performance as well. While any stock can see a spike in price, it takes a real winner to consistently outperform the market. Over the past quarter, shares of Grid Dynamics have risen 49.33%, and are up 53.91% in the last year. On the other hand, the S&P 500 has only moved 5.41% and 28.01%, respectively. Story Continues Investors should also pay attention to GDYN's average 20-day trading volume. Volume is a useful item in many ways, and the 20-day average establishes a good price-to-volume baseline; a rising stock with above average volume is generally a bullish sign, whereas a declining stock on above average volume is typically bearish. GDYN is currently averaging 606,429 shares for the last 20 days. Earnings Outlook The Zacks Momentum Style Score encompasses many things, including estimate revisions and a stock's price movement. Investors should note that earnings estimates are also significant to the Zacks Rank, and a nice path here can be promising. We have recently been noticing this with GDYN. Over the past two months, 4 earnings estimates moved higher compared to none lower for the full year. These revisions helped boost GDYN's consensus estimate, increasing from $0.32 to $0.34 in the past 60 days. Looking at the next fiscal year, 3 estimates have moved upwards while there have been 1 downward revision in the same time period. Bottom Line Given these factors, it shouldn't be surprising that GDYN is a #1 (Strong Buy) stock and boasts a Momentum Score of A. STEM Dips 43% in Six Months: Should You Buy, Sell or Hold the Stock? Zacks Equity Research Mon, Dec 30, 2024, 6:02 PM 5 min read Stem STEM, an artificial intelligence (AI)-enabled software and services company that empowers its clients to effectively plan, install and manage clean energy assets, has witnessed a drastic decline of 42.8% in six months, significantly underperforming the broader Zacks Computer and Technology sector and Computers - IT Services industry’s growth of 6.5% and 18.6%, respectively. Over the same time frame, Stem lagged behind its industry peers, including Vertiv VRT, Grid Dynamics GDYN and DXC Technology DXC. For the past six months, shares of GDYN, VRT and DXC have gained 119.3%, 32.8% and 8.5%, respectively. The underperformance is attributed to a significant decline in hardware sales, driven by weak demand for hardware systems. This situation is primarily due to financing delays and specific project-related interconnections. Additionally, the shift of customers toward solar services has further provoked a decline in storage hardware sales. The ongoing unpredictability in the timelines for utility-scale storage hardware projects has prompted Stem to adjust its strategy and reduce reliance on income from hardware sales. These scheduling challenges led to disappointing bookings and revenues. As a result, Stem's share price has suffered, reflecting concerns about the company's financial performance. This strategic shift aims to diversify revenue streams and mitigate the impact of ongoing market volatility. Stem, Inc. Price and Consensus Stem, Inc. Price and Consensus Stem, Inc. price-consensus-chart | Stem, Inc. Quote STEM’s Cautious Outlook for FY24 Stem’s underwhelming financial results in the third quarter of 2024 and YTD compelled it to lower its guidance for 2024. Revenues plunged by 78% in the third quarter and 70% over the first nine months of 2024 compared to the same period of the previous year, clearly indicating significant challenges ahead. Due to its weaker-than-expected financial performance in the first three quarters, Stem lowered its full-year 2024 revenue forecast range to $135-$155 million from $200-$270 million projected previously. The Zacks Consensus Estimate for 2024 revenues is pegged at $136.9 million, indicating a year-over-year decline of 70.3%. This lower revenue projection will significantly affect the value of bookings. Bookings are now forecasted to be between $100 million and $500 million, a decrease from the previous guidance of $600 million to $1.1 billion. On its third-quarter earnings call, Stem highlighted two main reasons for the decrease in booking value. First, there was a reduction in the resale of battery storage hardware included in its bookings. Second, there has been a gradual shift toward shorter software and service contracts in the storage sector, which now typically range from three to five years compared to the previous contracts that lasted between 15 and 20 years. Story Continues Business Transition to Limit STEM’s Growth STEM recently released a new business plan with a renewed focus on developing and marketing its AI-enabled software and services. This transition will necessitate significant operational changes, including a reduction in battery resales, which have historically generated the majority of revenues, changes to the way it produces and markets its products and services, and a realignment of the business processes. These changes, which are expected to result in lower revenues, higher expenses, and temporary disruptions in operations, may negatively impact the company's ability to successfully scale the software and services segments of the business and meet all operational and financial goals. Furthermore, various macroeconomic challenges, such as prolonged inflation, potential import tariffs, an economic slowdown and escalating geopolitical issues, including the conflicts between the United States and China and the uncertain impacts of current and future trade regulations, could adversely affect the stock market. Robust Offerings to Boost STEM’s Prospects STEM confidently asserts that its edge device and AI-enabled software are uniquely positioned to drive significant growth in renewable energy, even in a challenging economic environment. Stem recently unveiled that Mercuria Energy Trading has officially standardized on Stem’s PowerBidder Pro for effective bidding management and optimization strategies for a second clean energy asset within the Electric Reliability Council of Texas. The software was deployed in under 60 days after contract signing, highlighting its industry-leading integration and configuration capabilities. This rapid implementation empowered Mercuria’s trading teams to seize control of the asset without delay. This is the second Mercuria asset successfully supported by Stem’s PowerBidder Pro since Q3 2024, reinforcing Stem’s robust software and service-driven strategy aimed at achieving predictable, scalable growth and profitability for the company. STEM's recent launch of the PowerTrack Asset Performance Management suite revolutionizes how owners, operators, and asset managers manage their portfolios of storage, solar, and hybrid energy assets. This powerful software features customizable dashboards and workflows, allowing users to streamline data management and focus on what matters most. Furthermore, Stem and the Arizona Electric Power Cooperative, in collaboration with Prometheus Power, announced the successful completion of a solar and storage co-location project aimed at providing clean electricity to its distribution cooperatives and public power members. This project will utilize Stem’s award-winning AI-powered clean energy software, Athena, which will enable ongoing operation and monitoring of the storage system for optimal performance on a unified platform. What Should Investors Do With STEM Stock? Stem's AI-driven innovation and new business strategy may present a strong buying opportunity, though short-term challenges from macroeconomic uncertainties could pose risks. Additionally, STEM stock is not so cheap, as suggested by a Value Style Score of F. STEM currently carries a Zacks Rank #3 (Hold), implying that existing investors should keep holding the stock while new buyers should wait for a better entry point into the stock.
